<b>Asado</b> is a technique for <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../355/5355.xml">
cooking</link> cuts of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../940/18940.xml">
meat</link>, usually consisting of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../968/36968.xml">
beef</link> alongside various other meats, which are cooked on a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../389/3748389.xml">
grill</link> (<it>parrilla</it>) or open <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../145/11145.xml">
fire</link>. Asado is quite popular in the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../252/373252.xml">
Pampa</link> region of <system wordnetid="108435388" confidence="0.8">
<economy wordnetid="108366753" confidence="0.8">
<group wordnetid="100031264" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../769/26769.xml">
South America</link></group>
</economy>
</system>
, and it is the traditional dish of <city wordnetid="108524735" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../905/18951905.xml">
Argentina</link></country>
</city>
, <country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../843/31843.xml">
Uruguay</link></country>
, <body wordnetid="107965085" confidence="0.8">
<system wordnetid="108435388" confidence="0.8">
