,  and <country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../420/23420.xml">
Paraguay</link></country>
.            <p>

An asado typically has a sequence of meats presented by the <b>asador</b> (the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../469/584469.xml">
cooker</link>). First are the <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../617/335617.xml">
chorizo</link>s</it>, <it>morcillas</it> (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../722/215722.xml">
black pudding</link>), <it>chinchulines</it> (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../301/489301.xml">
chitterlings</link>), <it>mollejas</it> (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../664/28664.xml">
sweetbread</link>) and other <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../776/152776.xml">
organ</link>s, often accompanied by <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../033/5960033.xml">
provoleta</link></it>, a grilled cheese dish. Sometimes these are served on a coal-heated <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../147/1994147.xml">
brasero</link>. Then <it>costillas</it> or <it>asado de tira</it> (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../593/44593.xml">
ribs</link>) are served. Next comes <it>vacío</it> (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../704/1582704.xml">
flank steak</link>), <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../175/4182175.xml">
matambre</link></it> and possibly <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../402/37402.xml">
chicken</link> and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../843/31843.xml">
uruguay</link>an <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../221/1994221.xml">
chivito</link> (baby goat). Dishes such as the Uruguayan <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../210/5960210.xml">
Pamplona</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../929/19719929.xml">
pork</link> and <region wordnetid="108630985" confidence="0.8">
<region wordnetid="108630039" confidence="0.8">
